    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "adc67c24",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "adc67c24"
      },
      "source": [
        "### AdaGrad"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c76986c",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3c76986c"
      },
      "source": [
        "AdaGrad improves on regular gradient descent by having an adaptive learning rate, which leads to large steps for a low gradient (exploration), and small steps for a large gradient (exploitation). For this, you introduce $v_t$, which is the cumulative sum of all previous gradients squared.\n",
        "$$\\begin{align*}\n",
        "    v_0 &= 0\\\\\n",
        "    v_t &= v_{t-1} + g_t^2\\\\[2pt]\n",
        "    w_{t+1} &= w_t - \\frac{\\eta}{\\sqrt{v_t}+\\epsilon} \\cdot g_t\n",
        "\\end{align*}$$\n",
        "where $\\epsilon$ is a small value to avoid division by 0."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 92,
      "id": "87d18fa0",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "87d18fa0"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "## Question: What is the point of eps\n",
        "def ada_grad(learning_rate, num_iterations=30, x_start=-2.0, gradient=gradient, loss_function=loss_function):\n",
        "    eps = 1e-16\n",
        "    x = np.array(x_start)\n",
        "    losses = [loss_function(x)]\n",
        "    positions = [x]\n",
        "    vt = 0\n",
        "    for _ in range(num_iterations):\n",
        "        grad = np.array(gradient(x))\n",
        "        vt += grad**2\n",
        "        x = x - learning_rate * grad / (np.sqrt(vt) + eps)\n",
        "        losses.append(loss_function(x))\n",
        "        positions.append(x)\n",
        "\n",
        "    return positions, losses"
      ]
    },
